    <!-- SECTION 1: DOES IT WORK? -->
    <h2>Does Ashwagandha Work for Anxiety? The Evidence</h2>

    <p>Ashwagandha (<em>Withania somnifera</em>) is one of the few herbal supplements with a clinical evidence base that rivals pharmaceutical interventions for mild-to-moderate anxiety. Unlike many adaptogens that rely on traditional use claims, ashwagandha has been tested in multiple randomized, double-blind, placebo-controlled trials — the gold standard of medical evidence. The results are remarkably consistent across different research groups, populations, and extract types.</p>

    <div class="key-stat">
      <span class="key-stat-num">56.5%</span>
      <p class="key-stat-txt">reduction in Hamilton Anxiety Scale (HAM-A) scores was measured in a 2009 RCT published in <em>PLoS ONE</em>. <strong>Participants took 300mg of ashwagandha extract twice daily for 12 weeks</strong> — producing anxiolytic effects comparable to psychotherapy, without the sedation or dependence risk of pharmaceutical anxiolytics.</p>
    </div>

    <p>The strongest clinical evidence comes from seven key studies. Each used standardized ashwagandha extracts at defined doses and measured anxiety outcomes using validated clinical instruments:</p>

    <div class="tbl-wrap">
      <table>
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th>Study</th>
            <th>Dose</th>
            <th>Duration</th>
            <th>Key Finding</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr class="hl">
            <td><strong>Chandrasekhar et al. 2012</strong> — <em>Indian J Psych Med</em></td>
            <td>600mg KSM-66/day</td>
            <td>60 days</td>
            <td>27.9% cortisol reduction; significant anxiety and stress score improvement</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td><strong>Cooley et al. 2009</strong> — <em>PLoS ONE</em></td>
