    </div>

    <h3>Morning vs Night: When to Take Ashwagandha for Anxiety</h3>

    <p>Clinical trials have used both morning and evening dosing with positive results, so there is no single "correct" time. However, practical considerations can guide the decision. For generalized anxiety that affects you throughout the day, split dosing (300mg morning + 300mg evening) maintains more consistent withanolide levels. For anxiety that is worst at night or disrupts sleep, a single 600mg evening dose may be more effective. For anxiety with morning cortisol spikes, morning dosing aligns with your body's cortisol curve. The most important factor is consistency — pick a time, take it daily, and do not skip doses during the initial 8-week adaptation period.</p>

    <!-- SECTION 5: HOW LONG TO WORK -->
    <h2>How Long Does Ashwagandha Take to Work for Anxiety?</h2>

    <p>Ashwagandha is not a fast-acting anxiolytic. Unlike benzodiazepines (which work within 30 minutes) or even L-theanine (which produces calm within 30-60 minutes), ashwagandha works by gradually rebalancing HPA axis function over weeks of consistent daily use. Setting realistic timeline expectations is critical for compliance — most people who "give up" on ashwagandha do so before the compound has reached its full anxiolytic potential.</p>

    <div class="num-steps">
      <div class="num-step">
        <span class="num-step-n">1</span>
        <div>
          <h3>Days 1-14: Subtle Shifts</h3>
          <p>During the first two weeks, ashwagandha's GABAergic activity may produce a mild calming effect. Some users report feeling slightly less reactive to daily stressors and falling asleep more easily. Clinical instruments typically do not detect statistically significant anxiety reduction this early. Continue taking your daily dose — the compound is beginning to modulate HPA axis signaling.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="num-step">
        <span class="num-step-n">2</span>
        <div>
          <h3>Weeks 2-4: Measurable Cortisol Reduction</h3>
          <p>By week 2-4, serum cortisol begins to decline measurably (11-15% in studies). You may notice that stressful situations feel less overwhelming, that you recover from stressors faster, and that physical anxiety symptoms (muscle tension, racing heart, digestive issues) begin to diminish. Sleep quality typically begins improving during this window.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="num-step">
        <span class="num-step-n">3</span>
        <div>
          <h3>Weeks 4-8: Full Anxiolytic Effect</h3>
          <p>This is when the majority of clinical trials measure their primary endpoints. Cortisol reduction reaches 20-28% in most studies. Anxiety scores on validated instruments (HAM-A, PSS, DASS) show 40-57% improvement versus placebo. The HPA axis has reached a new, lower-cortisol baseline. Most users report noticeable, sustained anxiety reduction by week 6-8.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="num-step">
        <span class="num-step-n">4</span>
        <div>
          <h3>Weeks 8-12: Sustained Benefit + Secondary Effects</h3>
          <p>By week 8-12, the full adaptogenic benefit is established. Anxiety reduction stabilizes at its new baseline. Secondary benefits — improved sleep architecture, better cognitive focus, reduced inflammation markers, and (in men) modest testosterone improvement — reach their peak. Long-term studies show these benefits are maintained with continued daily use.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

