    <h3>Common Non-Serious Side Effects</h3>

    <p>The most commonly reported side effects in clinical trials are mild gastrointestinal symptoms — nausea, stomach discomfort, or diarrhea — which typically resolve within the first week and are minimized by taking ashwagandha with food. Some users report drowsiness, particularly at higher doses or when taken in the evening. Rarely, vivid dreams have been reported, likely related to ashwagandha's effect on sleep architecture and cortisol. None of these side effects have led to study discontinuation in clinical trials at recommended doses.</p>

    <!-- FAQ SECTION -->
    <section class="faq-sec">
      <h2>Ashwagandha for Anxiety — Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
      <details class="fq"><summary>How much ashwagandha should I take for anxiety?</summary><p>The clinically effective dose for anxiety is 300-600mg of KSM-66 ashwagandha per day, or 125-250mg of Sensoril per day. The landmark 2012 study used 300mg of KSM-66 twice daily (600mg total) and achieved a 56.5% reduction in anxiety scores. Start at 300mg per day and increase to 600mg after 2 weeks if well tolerated.</p></details>
      <details class="fq"><summary>How long does ashwagandha take to work for anxiety?</summary><p>Most studies show measurable anxiety reduction within 2-4 weeks, with full benefits at 6-8 weeks. The 2012 trial measured its primary endpoint at 60 days. Some users notice subtle calming effects within the first week from ashwagandha's GABAergic activity, but clinically significant HPA axis modulation requires sustained daily use over several weeks.</p></details>
      <details class="fq"><summary>Is ashwagandha better than medication for anxiety?</summary><p>Ashwagandha should not replace prescription anxiety medication without physician guidance. One study found effects comparable to lorazepam (Ativan) without sedation or dependence risk. However, prescription medications are appropriate for severe anxiety, panic disorder, and acute episodes. Ashwagandha may be suitable for mild-to-moderate generalized anxiety or as a complementary approach.</p></details>
      <details class="fq"><summary>Can I take ashwagandha with anti-anxiety medication?</summary><p>Ashwagandha may interact with benzodiazepines (additive sedation), SSRIs (serotonergic interaction), and thyroid medications. Never combine with prescription anti-anxiety medication without explicit physician approval. If approved, start at the lowest ashwagandha dose and monitor for excessive sedation or mood changes.</p></details>
      <details class="fq"><summary>What is the best form of ashwagandha for anxiety?</summary><p>KSM-66 has the most clinical evidence for anxiety (24+ RCTs). Sensoril is also effective with higher withanolide concentration. The delivery format (gummy, capsule, powder) does not affect efficacy — the critical factor is extract type and dose. Gummies offer superior compliance for daily use.</p></details>
      <details class="fq"><summary>Does ashwagandha help with social anxiety?</summary><p>The mechanisms that reduce generalized anxiety (cortisol reduction, HPA axis modulation, GABAergic activity) are relevant to social anxiety. One study included participants with social anxiety components and found significant improvement. However, no large-scale trial has studied ashwagandha exclusively for social anxiety disorder. It may be helpful as part of a broader approach including therapy.</p></details>
      <details class="fq"><summary>Is KSM-66 or Sensoril better for anxiety?</summary><p>Both have strong evidence. KSM-66 has the broader evidence base (24+ trials) and is used in most anxiety-specific studies. Sensoril has higher withanolide concentration (10% vs 5%), requiring a lower dose, with strong cortisol reduction data. For anxiety specifically, both are excellent choices. KSM-66 has more overall evidence; Sensoril may be slightly more potent per milligram for cortisol.</p></details>
      <details class="fq"><summary>Can ashwagandha make anxiety worse?</summary><p>Rarely. Worsening anxiety has been reported in people with hyperthyroidism (ashwagandha stimulates thyroid hormones), nightshade sensitivity, or when taken on an empty stomach (GI distress can mimic anxiety). If anxiety worsens, reduce dose, take with food, and consult your healthcare provider. Discontinue if symptoms persist.</p></details>
    </section>

    <!-- VERDICT -->
    <div class="verdict">
      <h3>The Evidence-Based Verdict: Ashwagandha for Anxiety</h3>
      <p>Ashwagandha is one of the most well-validated natural anxiolytics available. Multiple randomized controlled trials demonstrate 40-57% reductions in anxiety scores, 27.9% cortisol reduction, and effects comparable to psychotherapy and lorazepam — without the sedation, cognitive impairment, or dependence risk of pharmaceutical anxiolytics.</p>
      <p>The critical requirements for efficacy are: (1) use a standardized extract — KSM-66 or Sensoril, not generic powder; (2) take the clinical dose — 300-600mg KSM-66 or 125-250mg Sensoril per day; (3) be consistent for at least 6-8 weeks before evaluating results; and (4) consult your physician if you have thyroid conditions, autoimmune disease, are pregnant, or take prescription medications. Meet these four criteria, and the science is clear — ashwagandha works for anxiety.</p>
